Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterParts of a Plant5
There are different plants around us. All plants have two main parts: one 
below the ground and the other above the ground.
The part of the plant that grows below the ground it called the root system. 
The part of the plant that grows above the ground is called the shoot system. 
The shoot system consists of stem, leaves, flowers and fruits.
! Look at the picture and label different parts of a plant.
! Which part of the plant grows below the soil?
Environmental Studies-439Unit–II : The Living World

Tap roots– A tap root is a thick, single root 
that does not have any branches.
Pea, Radish, turnip, carrot are examples 
of plants having tap root etc.
Fibrous roots– A fibrous root grows from the base 
of the stem and has many branches. All types of 
grasses, wheat and rice have fibrous roots.
Special Types of RootsBesides the basic functions performed by them, there are some roots that perform 
special functions.
Water storing roots– Roots of some plants like pumpkin and gourd store water for 
the plant to survive long during the dry summer months.
Food storing roots– Some roots store extra food in them. Such roots are used in 
our kitchens and are an important part of our food. Carrot, radish, beetroot, turnip, 
sweet-potato etc. are their examples.
CarrotRadishTurnipRoots of PlantsThe roots fix the plant in the soil. They absorb water and minerals from the soil. 
There are two main types of roots: tap roots and fibrous roots.
Environmental Studies-440

The Shoot SystemThe shoot system includes all those parts of a 
plant that grow above the ground. A shoot 
system has– stem, leaves, flowers and fruits.
Stem– It carries water, minerals and food 
prepared by the leaves to all parts of the 
plant. The stem bears leaves, buds, flowers 
and fruits.
Leaves– The leaves are mostly green in 
colour. They make food for the plant and 
therefore, called the kitchen of the plant. We 
eat leave of many plant such as spinach, 
lettuce, cabbage etc.
Green leafy vegetables are good for health. Leaves of some plants e.g. neem, tulsi, 
eucalyptus etc. are used in medicines.
StemLeavesFlowers– Flowers are the most beautiful 
part of a plant and have different shapes, 
sizes, colours and smells. Flowers grow 
into fruits.
Different flowersProp roots– Some trees like the banyan tree 
have roots that grow from the branches and 
reach the ground. Sometimes, they get 
attached to the soil and provide additional 
support to the plant.
Such roots that grow from the branches above 
the ground, are called prop roots or aerial 
roots. Ficus and peepal tree also grow aerial 
roots as their age increases.
Banyan treeEnvironmental Studies-441

You 
 KnowMust 
Marigold flowers keep mosquitoes and flies away.
Flowers in Our LivesFlowers bring colours and freshness to our surroundings and homes. We use 
flowers in a number of ways.
1. 
To offer prayers— In places of worship we use fresh flowers for decoration 
and to offer prayers.
2. 
As food—We eat flowers of cauliflower, broccoli, banana and pumpkin as 
vegetables. Rose water and rose petals are used to flavour sweets.
3. 
For making perfumes— Some flowers are used for making perfumes, soaps 
and shampoos.
4. 
For greeting– We greet people with a bouquet of flowers to express our 
emotions on special days.
5. 
For making dyes and colours– Petals of some flowers are used to make dry 
colours called gulal during Holi celebration. Many dyes are also prepared 
with them.
 
Besides many other uses, women adorn themselves by wearing flowers in 
their hair.
Plants are a lovely gift of nature. Human beings or animals cannot live without 
plants. We must look after plants and protect forest.
Fruits– A fruit is the sweet and fleshy product that has seeds inside.
The seeds produce new plants.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterFood and HealthUnit–III : Our Needs6
Good health means the state of over all well-being of a person. We cannot buy 
good heath from anywhere. It is to be maintained by taking care of certain 
things. The key to good health lies in our daily activities. One of them is eating 
healthy food.
Look at the given picture. Roma is enjoying jalebis from a street vendor .
! Is it a healthy practice?
! Should we eat uncovered street food?
Healthy FoodWe should eat foods that provide us energy and help in growth of our body. Junk 
food and cold, sugary drinks are not good for health.
We must follow good eating habits, too, to maintain good health. Some of them 
are–
! Wash hands before and after the meals.
! Add fruits and salad in your diet.
Environmental Studies-447

You 
 KnowMust 
! Eat properly cooked food.
! Keep all the food items covered.
! Use clean water and clean utensils.
Food contains different useful substances called nutrients, which are needed by 
our body for various purposes.
The main nutrients needed by our body are–
! Carbohydrates 
 
 
 
Fats
! Proteins 
 
 
 
Vitamins & MineralsBesides, food also contains roughage and water which are essential for proper 
functioning of our body.
Carbohydrates– Carbohydrates provide energy to the body. The rich sources of 
carbohydrates are: bread, cereals, potato, sugar, honey, jam etc.
Eating healthy food fills your body with energy.
Fats– Fats are a richer source of energy than carbohydrates. Excess carbohydrates 
are converted into fats and stored in the body. Fats and carbohydrates together are 
known as energy-giving foods . Rich sources of fats are: butter, ghee, oil, nuts, dry-fruits, meat etc.
bread, cereals, potato, sugar, honey, jam(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-448

Proteins– Proteins are needed for growth. They also repair the damaged cells. So, 
they are called body-building food. Milk, eggs, pulses, cheese, fish, meat etc. are 
some good sources of proteins.
Vitamins and Minerals– Vitamins and minerals protect our body from various 
diseases and keep us healthy and strong. This is the reason, they are called the 
protective foods. Vitamins help us to have a good vision healthy gums, and a 
glowing skin. There are different kinds of vitamins. These are: Vitamin A, Vitamin B, 
Vitamin C, Vitamin D, Vitamin E. and Vitamin K. Fresh fruits, vegetables, meat, fish , 
milk and eggs are rich in vitamins.
Minerals help in the formation of blood, bones and teeth. Main minerals needed 
by our body are: calcium, iron, sodium and potassium. Calcium is needed for 
healthy teeth and strong bones. Iron helps in the formation of blood.
Green leafy vegetables, fruits, milk, fish etc. are good sources of minerals.
Roughage– Roughage is the fibrous material present in cereals, fruits and 
vegetables. It is required for proper functioning of the digestive system. It helps in 
the removal of waste material from the large intestine and prevents constipation.
Environmental Studies-449

You 
 KnowMust 
Water– Besides nutrients and roughage, our body also needs sufficient amount of 
water to stay healthy. Water helps us:
! in digestion of food.
! to remove wastes (in the form of urine and sweat) from the body.
! to maintain our body temperature.
We must drink at least 8-10 glasses of water everyday.
Almost two-third of our body weight consists of water.
Balanced Diet– A diet which contains all the 
nutrients, roughage and water in the right amount 
is called a balanced diet.
We must eat balanced diet for proper functioning of 
our body.
DiseasesDisease is defined as the condition in which our body does not function properly. 
Diseases are of two types–
Communicable diseases– These diseases are caused by germs or microbes. They 
can spread through contaminated food, water, air, insect bites or contact with 
infected persons. Examples of such type of diseases are–
Common cold, tuberculosis, measles, typhoid, dengue, cholera, Covid-19 etc.
To prevent such diseases, the best method is to maintain proper hygiene of body, 
food, water and surroundings.
Non-Communicable or deficiency diseases– Non communicable diseases do not 
spread from one person to another. They may occur due to deficiency of one or 
more nutrients in our body. So, they are also called deficiency diseases. Examples 
are– anaemia, rickets, goitre etc.
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-450

! Obesity– Excessive intake of carbohydrates and fats 
which causes excessive body weight.
Diseases due to faulty life style
! Malnutrition– It is also called under-nutrition. It is the 
result of not having enough food or enough of the 
right kind of foodHygiene is necessary to stay healthy and keep away diseases. It is defined as the 
science of cleanliness which helps ensure good health. The following are some of 
the steps for maintaining proper hygiene:
! Take bath daily. It removes dust and sweat present on our body.
! Wash your hands after using the toilets. If we do not wash our hands properly, 
germs and dirt enter our body.
! Keep your surroundings clean. Do not throw garbage in open. The garbage in 
open attracts flies and mosquitoes.
! Let fresh air and sunlight enter into the house. Sunlight kills germs.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterFrom Farm to Our PlateUnit–III : Our Needs7
We all need food for our survival. It gives us energy to do work. But have we 
ever thought where does all this food come from? The foods we eat travel a 
long journey before they reach our plates. They are produced in the (farms) 
by the farmers.
! Put a tick (3) below the healthy food items and cross (7) for the 
unhealthy ones.
! Where does this food come from?
Look at the pictures of food items given below.
The mass production of plants for food and other purposes is called agriculture or 
farming.
The various steps of farming are–
1. Ploughing– Farmers prepare the soil by loosening it through a special process 
known as ploughing. The ploughs may be attached to the bullock carts or the 
tractors.
The Farmers at the FarmsEnvironmental Studies-455

2. Manuring– After ploughing, the farmers add manure and fertilizers to the soil to 
provide nutrients to the soil. This increases the productivity of the soil.
3. Levelling– After manuring, the soil is levelled to make the surface even.
4. Sowing Seeds–Healthy seeds are sown in the soil after levelling. Seeds can be 
sown manually or with the help of machines. These seeds grow into saplings 
afer getting right amount of warmth, water and air.
The packed crops are transported to the wholesale market commonly called mandi 
for selling. Carts, trucks, tractors etc. are used to transport the food crops to 
market. 
Shopkeepers and vendors from towns or cities come to the mandi and buy the 
products in bulk. They then, sell them in their shops at a higher rate to make profit. 
From Farm to Mandi6. Spraying pesticides– When the crops grow, farmers spray insecticides and 
pesticides to protect the crop from insects and pests like rats, termites etc. Scare 
crows are kept in the crop field to scare away birds.
7. Harvesting– When the crops are ripe, they are cut and gathered. This process is 
called harvesting. Harvesting is done by sickles or machines called harvesters. 
The farmers then separate the ripened seeds from the plants. This is called 
threshing. Then they remove the husk from the grains. This is called winnowing.
 
The harvested crops need to be stored properly in granaries to protect them 
from rodents like rats, squirrels etc. Vegetables and fruits get spoilt fast, so they 
have to be sold quickly.
5. Irrigation– After the seeds are sown, the 
fields need to be watered regularly. This is 
called irrigation. The various means of 
irrigation are— wells, tube-wells, canals.
Environmental Studies-456

A large number of people work hard in making food available to us. We should be 
thankful to all of them. We should not waste food. We should always remember 
that there are many people who do not get enough food to eat. Some ways by 
which we can prevent the wastage of food are–
! Buy food items in the required quantities only.
! Avoid unnecessary cooking.
! Keep the leftover food in the refrigerator.
! Try to reuse the leftover food by making new recipes.
! Maintain the correct temperature in refrigerator to keep the food fresh for a 
longer duration of time.
! Always take as much food in your plate that you can finish easily.
Avoid Food WastageThe small shopkeepers who buy the products from wholesalers for selling in their 
shops are called retailers or grocers. We (the consumers) buy these products from
